@import ../../docs/convo-core.md !file
> user
Content messages such as user, system and assistant are being highlighted like script blocks
such as define and do messages.

And try to make the color schema match TypeScript



@time 2026-04-19T06:58:44-04:00
@tokenUsage 77871 / 792
@model open-router/anthropic/claude-4.7-opus-20260416
> assistant
Got it. Before I make the change, one clarification to get it right the first time:

In the original TM grammar:
- `> user`, `> system`, `> assistant`, and any role not explicitly listed are `content roles` — their body should look like prose (default/plain text), not code.
- `> define`, `> do`, `> debug`, `> result`, `> thinkingResult`, `> end`, `> target`, `> make`, `> stage`, `> app` are `top-level script` roles — their body should highlight as code.
- `> function_name(...)` is a function role — code body.
- `> node`, `> nodeEnd`, `> goto`, `> exitGraph`, `> to`, `> from`, `> exit` are special.

Plan:
1. Track the current role context: `content | script | function | special | none`.
2. In `content` mode, stop doing full code tokenization of the body. Only highlight:
   - tags `@...`
   - embeds `\{{ ... }}`
   - inline code `` ` ` ``
   - strings (dq/sq) — optional, but original grammar still parses them in content messages
   - special words like `$$RAG$$`
   - xml tags
   - markdown links
   - comments at line start
   - `???...???` and `===...===`
   - otherwise just emit no token (plain text)
3. In `script`/`function` mode, use the full expression tokenizer (what it does today).
4. Match a TypeScript-style palette (VS Code Dark+ TS coloring):
   - keyword: `#569CD6`
   - control flow keyword: `#C586C0`
   - storage modifier (public, local, agent): `#569CD6`
   - function name: `#DCDCAA`
   - type: `#4EC9B0`
   - string: `#CE9178`
   - number: `#B5CEA8`
   - comment: `#6A9955`
   - variable: `#9CDCFE`
   - property: `#9CDCFE`
   - operator: `#D4D4D4`
   - builtin/constant (true, false, null): `#569CD6`
   - tag/attribute: `#D7BA7D`
   - bracket: default text

Question before I proceed: Do you want hard-coded TypeScript-like colors for both light and dark Obsidian themes, or only dark theme (which is how VS Code TS colors are typically seen)? Also, should light theme fall back to Obsidian defaults?


> user
The plan looks good.

Add support for both light and dark mode

